07717nmm a2200853Ia 9780814749388DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20012001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147493887 a10.18574/nyu/9780814749388.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)680941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0460002bisacsh1 aKaplan, Leonard V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAftermath :bThe Clinton Impeachment and the Presidency in the Age of Political Spectacle /cLeonard V. Kaplan; ed. by Beverly Moran. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical America ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Politics -- t1 A Case Study in Group Polarization (with Warnings for the Future) -- t2 Sex and Politics at the Close of the Twentieth Century: A Feminist Looks Back at the Clinton Impeachment and the Thomas Confirmation Hearings -- t3 Public, Private, and the Gender Division of Emotional Labor -- t4 Everything You Thought You Knew about Impeachment Is Wrong -- t5 Pierre Elliot Trudeau: A Canadian Scandal? -- tPart II Law -- t6 Comparing the Independent Counsel to Other Prosecutors: Privilege and Other Issues -- t7 Legalizing Outrage -- t8 The Gold Standard and Guilt-Edged Insecurities: The Impeachment Crucible as Tragic Farce -- t9 Sex, Harm, and Impeachment -- t10 Impeachment: A (Civil) Religious Perspective -- t11 The Constitutional Politics of the Clinton Impeachment -- tPart III Shaping Public Opinion -- t12 Ontology in the Clinton Era -- t13 All We Had to Do Was Rationalize the Sex -- t14 Perjury and Impeachment: The Rule of Law or the Rule of Lawyers? -- t15 Impeachment and Enchanting Arts -- t16 A Year after the Acquittal in the Impeachment Trial -- tPart IV Religion -- t17 An Un-Christian Pursuit -- t18 Abuse of Power as a Cultural Construct -- t19 Bill Clinton and the American Character -- t20 The Clinton Scandal: Law and Morals -- tPart V The Political Is Personal -- t21 The Spectacle and the Libertine -- t22 The Political Is Personal -- tConclusion: The Penultimate: The Meaning of Impeachment and Liberal Governance -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the specter of prosecution after his term is over and the possibility of disbarment in Arkansas hanging over President Clinton, the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal and the events that have followed it show no sign of abating. The question has become what to do, and how to think, about those eight months. Did the President lie or was it plausible that he had truthfully testified to no sexual relationship? Was the job search for Monica just help for a friend or a sinister means of obtaining silence? Even if all the charges were true, did impeachment follow or was censure enough? And what are the lasting repercussions on the office of the Presidency? Aftermath: The Clinton Impeachment and the Presidency in the Age of Political Spectacle takes a multi-disciplinary approach to analyze the Clinton impeachment from political perspectives across the spectrum. The authors attempt to tease out the meanings of the scandal from the vantage point of law, religion, public opinion, and politics, both public and personal. Further, the impeachment itself is situated broadly within the contemporary American liberal state and mined for the contradictory possibilities for reconciliation it reveals in our culture. Contributors: David T. Canon, John Cooper, Drucilla Cornell, Jean Bethke Elshtain, Robert W. Gordon, Lawrence Joseph, Leonard V. Kaplan, David Kennedy, Kenneth R. Mayer, Beverly I. Moran, Father Richard John Neuhaus, David Novak, Linda Denise Oakley, Elizabeth Rapaport, Lawrence Rosen, Eric Rothstein, Aviam Soifer, Lawrence M. Solan, Cass R. Sunstein, Stephen Toulmin, Leon Trakman, Frank Tuerkheimer, Mark V. Tushnet, Andrew D. Weiner, Robin L. West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aTrials (Impeachment) - United States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Commentary & Opinion.2bisacsh1 aCanon, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, John Milton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElshtain, Jean Bethke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Leonard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer, Kenneth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Beverly I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Beverly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNeuhaus, Richard John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOakley, Linda Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapaport, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosen, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoifer, Aviam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolan, Lawrence M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSunstein, Cass R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v